SIMPLE: interlard
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Interlard
<hw>In`ter*lard"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp.
& p. p.</pos> <conjf>Interlarded</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Interlarding</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[F. <ets>entrelarder</ets>.
See <er>Inter-</er>, and <er>Lard</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>To place lard or bacon amongst; to mix, as fat meat
with lean.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Whose grain doth rise in flakes, with fatness
<qex>interlarded</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Drayton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence: To insert between; to mix or mingle;
especially, to introduce that which is foreign or irrelevant; <as>as, to
<ex>interlard</ex> a conversation with oaths or
allusions</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The English laws . . . [were] mingled and <qex>interlarded</qex>
with many particular laws of their own.</q> <rj><qau>Sir M.
Hale.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They <qex>interlard</qex> their native drinks with choice⟦br⟧
Of strongest brandy.</q> <rj><qau>J. Philips.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Interlay</ent>⟦br⟧
